            <span class="utterance" who="#minskiJ" start="3252.527" end="x">. . . an 'ox tail,' yes [Footnote 5: The German word Schwanz means in regular parlance 'a tail;' in slang it stands for 'penis.' It was common in the Russian Czarist Army for higher officers, viz the Grand Duke Nikolas, to use a dryed and specially stretched ox penis as a riding crop, with which in moments of 'noble ire' they would strike even subordinate officers. The ox penis makes apparently not only a hardhitting whip, but a stroke with it implied a component of contempt for the victim.] .</span>
